State opened Covid vaccines to 50 and over on Mon, March 22. I immediately scheduled my appointment for a first shot at a Dept of Health site near me for Wed, March 24. I had no immediate negative side effects. When I woke on Fri, March 26 and commenced my day of remote work from home, I noticed my left eye vision was blurry. I proceeded to work that day and continued my normal activities into the weekend assuming my vision would self-correct. By Sunday, March 26, my left eye vision was still noticeably problematic so I scheduled to see an optometrist whom I had seen before. I saw him at 12:15pm on Tues, March 30. After running numerous vision tests, optometrist let me know my vision loss in the left eye seemed to be the result of a stroke that had cut blood flow in the optic nerve and damaged my vision in the lower portions of the left eye. The center and upper portions of my left eye were generally unaffected at that time. He suggested I see my primary care physician to check for vitals, such as blood pressure and do other blood work, and more importantly see a neuro ophthalmologist urgently.   The next morning, Wed, March 31 I saw my PCP, who informed me my blood pressure was normal, requested blood work, and gave me a prescription for an MRI of my brain, with and without contrast. I am 6'2" and I weighed at 239, about where it has been for most of last 15 years. I also complained of pain and stiffness in my front right thigh and lower right back. She said if I didn't get an appointment to see a neuro ophthalmologist that same afternoon, she recommended I go to an ER. With the help of Optometrist's office, I was able to get an appointment that day with Dr., neuro ophthalmologist at 2:15pm on Wed, March 31. His office repeated numerous vision tests and confirmed the left eye vision loss (essentially the lower half excluding the center) and diagnosed it as a NAION - non arthritic ischemic optic neuropathy. With this diagnosis, there was no treatment, and I scheduled a follow-up for May 12. He said that my optic nerve into my left eye would slowly reduce its swelling over the next 6 to 8 weeks and in that time, my vision could remain the same, or improve. At that point, I didn't think it would worsen, but sadly that later happened. In addition to the the first MRI that PCP prescribed, Neuro ophthalmologist prescribed a second MRI of orbits, with and without contrast. He also suggested I begin taking a low dose Aspirin daily, which I did.   The next week, the blood work revealed a very slightly elevated cholesterol reading. I was told by my PCP on April 5 that this would normally not be considered as a problematic level of high cholesterol, but should be improved or lowered. The blood tests taken at Lab on Fri, April 2 revealed a LDL Chol, Calculated as 111, whereby <100 was considered desirable range. Other than that, there was nothing of concern in my blood work. The two MRIs were done on April 9 and April 20, and did not reveal findings which doctors felt would have impacted my optic nerve swelling or had caused the eye stroke. Out of precaution, I scheduled to see a cardiologist on Tues, April 13. She recommended I start taking Crestor for cholesterol, and do a series of tests which I completed on Friday, April 23 - echocardiogram; holter monitor; transesophageal echocardiogram; and ultrasound carotid bilateral. As of today, Mon, April 26 I do not know the results of the cardio work-up, but both neuro ophthalmologists I saw felt that a problem related to my heart would not have caused this stroke in my eye.   Finally, on Fri, April 23 I had a consultation with a second highly recommended neuro ophthalmologist. After a series of vision tests, she agreed with other doctor's diagnosis of NAION - non arthritic ischemic optic neuropathy. She also said there was nothing I could do to treat except wait for the next 4 or more weeks for the optic nerve swelling to go down. She also confirmed my fear which was that my left eye vision had worsened since March 31 as my vision loss was no longer limited to the lower portion of my left eye, but now included blind spots throughout the upper range of my left eye vision, making my loss of peripheral vision worse and more widespread. She said in some cases with NAION, a patient's vision could remain the same, could improve or could worsen in the 6 to 8 weeks after the event. Four weeks after the March 26 event, by April 23 my left eye vision had worsened. I still hold out hope that it can improve some in the next four weeks... My right eye vision was not affected in any way, although one risk of NAION is that there is a 20% (?) chance it may recur in the next 5 years, and if it does, it most commonly affects the other, good eye.   None of the doctors I saw directly attributed my vision loss to the Moderna vaccine taken on March 24; however, there has also not been a clear cause determined by my doctors. While most of the doctors I saw seemed to think it coincidental, none also was able to absolutely rule it out either as a cause or a trigger. Dr. suggested I follow through with this idea, which other medical professionals suggested, to submit this vaccine adverse event report. Without a doubt, this was an adverse effect and/or problem that occurred soon after (36 hours approximately) taking the first dose of the Moderna vaccine.
LAB_DATA: explained in description of adverse event, treatment, and outcome.
OTHER_MEDS: lithium carbonate, occassional ibuprofen or ibuprofen PM

On 04/25/21 at 12:30pm, patient received first dose of Moderna Vaccine. Patient was clear-headed and alert, but appeared anxious at the time of receiving the vaccine. 15 minutespost vaccination, patient suddenly fainted to ground within pharmacist?s sight. RPh on duty immediately ran to patient and called for help. Patient remained laying down, until he was able to open his eyes and safely sit up.   RPh on duty and front end managers were at the scene, patient was provided with water and offered 911/ambulance for help. Patient denied, stating he "is fine" and wanted to sit down before deciding before calling 911. Per pt, he didn?t think he hit his head when he fainted, but he fell on the side of his temple. RPH on duty observed patient for another 30 minutes until 1:15PM. Per patient, he only had a small breakfast and a kombucha in the morning. He also has history of fainting/anxiousness from vaccine about 20 years ago, and another fainting history while he was taking an exam. Patient mentioned he was very anxious prior to receiving the shot. Patient doesn't have any medical history and is not taking any medications or other illicit drugs. Patient lives by himself so he doesn't have anyone to watch over him when he goes home and at 1:15PM. Patient stated he still feels dizzy, nausea, and arm tingling. Front end manager called 911/Ambulance, medics arrived around 1:20PM. blood glucose, blood pressure, pulse and oxygen were checked. Medics also checked patient?s memory (asked what day it was, what year, who the president is, etc). Medics told patient that he can decide the following options:   1: to have family/friend to come pick him up and take him home OR 2: they can take him to nearby hospital for checkup. Patient lives alone so he decided to go to the hospital to have check up to "make him feel better".  Patient was transported to the hospital around 1:37 PM. Both RPh on duty and front end managers were at the scene the whole time. Patient seemed to be in full command of his faculties and was following instructions at time of departure. Prior to leaving the premise, patient was advised to have someone accompany him at next dose appointment by RPh on duty.  Caring call was made around 9:20AM the next day 4/26/2021. LM was left and wait for patient response. Store Director and Pharmacy Manager were notified. Pharmacy District Manager was called for alternative administration options for second dose.

Friday morning abbout 3-3:30 am, I took one Tylenol.   At about 4 am  i was very nauseous and thought i better try to get to bathroom.   I started to get out of bed and had both feet on floor when apparently i passed out and fell back into the bed.   I never felt like i was going to pass out.  I had no warning.  I was just out! My husband said i then started to make weird sounds, like i was throwing up (but didn't throw up).   I then went silent and he spent about 45 seconds to 1 minute shaking me and hollering my name continuously trying to get me to respond.  He said he couldn?t detect a breathe.   He said i finally took a huge loud deep breathe and came to. I don't recall any of the above.  All i recall is hearing someone very faintly calling my name over and over but i could not respond.   When i finally came to, i realized i had relieved myself in the bed and was very nauseous and threw up.  After that had severe chills, and extreme fatigue all day.  I ended up sleeping all day.  Had nausea quite a bit of the day.  Had light headaches towards the end of the day.  Slept all Friday night.  Got up Saturday and felt fine (about 98% back to normal).   Since then have had soreness at injection site and tiredness.   Just thought you might want to know my reaction to the 2nd shot. I am worried about taking a booster shot in the future if this was my reaction to the 2nd shot.

She got ?very sick? after her second injection.  She says the injection induced suicidal ideation.  She had thoughts to hang herself which she has not had previously.  She said, ?if I wasn?t in so much physical pain and couldn?t move I would have done it?my whole body was in pain?it is like I had COVID all over again except the breathing part?.I couldn?t move.?  She was ?curled up on the floor in the closet.?  The suicidal ideation resolved after 1.5 days at the same time as the body aches resolved.  She is not sure if the suicidal ideation was a side effect to the injection or triggered by the body aches from the vaccination.  She had not had any suicidal ideation in the timeframe prior to the vaccination.  Her last suicidal ideation prior to this event was about one year ago.  She has not had any suicidal ideation since the 1.5 days after the vaccination.  She was also having trouble recalling information during the 1.5 days after the injection  or ?form complete sentences?I would forget things mid-word.?   The cognitive effects lasted 1.5 days.  She did not have any adverse effects after 1.5 days.  She did not cut or have any urges to cut.  She last had urges to cut a couple of months ago.  She did not have any illicit drug or alcohol or marijuana use during that timeframe.  She thinks the body aches and suicidal ideation developed at the same time (as compared to one starting before the other).  She also had chills but did not check her temperature.  She did not take any NSAIDS or Tylenol.  She did not experience any other acute psychiatric symptoms during the 1.5 days.  She did not have psychosis, mania, depression, PTSD or OCD triggered.  She did not have any new medications during this timeframe.  Her COVID 19 infection was in March of 2020.  She thinks it is possible that the vaccination was a ?trigger? to suicidal ideation because during her COVID-19 infection she wondered if she was going to survive.  She did not have suicidal ideation back in March of 2020 during her COVID-19 infection.  She said her ?resolve? to kill herself was unique for the 1.5 days stating, ?the only reason I didn?t do it was I couldn?t get up.?  She did not go to the hospital ?because I had no way to get there.?  She realizes she should have called 911.  The experience was ?scary.?  She said she did not think about calling me adding, ?I didn?t know what to do?I couldn?t think straight...I couldn?t even remember my birthday but I do that a lot?my birthday was never celebrated.?  She had the Pfizer vaccination.  The only side effects after the first injection of the vaccine was congestion and a sore arm (both of which lasted three days).  She does not recall having congestion after the second injection.  She reports that she is fine now.   She thinks she had suicidal ideation triggered by a past psychiatric medication as well but she cannot recall which medication.

Thrombocytopenia with onset 12 days after vaccination. Vaccine occurred on 3/15/21, thrombocytopenia (platelet count of 0) discovered on 3/27/21 in the context of GI bleed (hematemesis) and drop of Hemoglobin from 11.2 (baseline) to 8.3.
LAB_DATA: Patient was transferred to tertiary medical center where he underwent typical treatment for GI bleed and was transfused blood and platelets. Hematology was consulted for suspected ITP given the precipitous drop in platelets from baseline of ~70 down to 0. Patient was treated with IVIG and Dexamethasone. Will copy and paste Hematology follow-up note from 4/15/21. Patient was discharged on 4/2/21. Hematology & Oncology Clinic   Impression/Plan: # Iron deficiency anemia. S/P ferric carboxymaltose during hospital admission on 4/2/21. Hgb 11.3, iron toal 90, iron sat 21%, ferritin 161, TIBC 430. No evidence of recurrent GI bleed. He will follow-up with Dr. in 3 months with repeat CBC with differential and iron studies for ongoing monitoring.     # Chronic thrombocytopenia (baseline 50-80k).  #Liver cirrhosis, compensated. Plt 63k. S/p 6-pack platelets x4 during recent hospitalization. Also, received IVIG x2 with and 3 doses of high-dose oral dexamethasone with minimal response, therefore ITP less likely. Patient denies active bleeding, melena, hematochezia, or hematemesis. Patient historically has lower platelet counts likely secondary to end-stage liver disease. Will recheck CBC in 1 month and 3 months. Transfuse to keep platelets greater than 50,000 in setting of active bleeding.    # History of alcohol abuse.  # End-stage liver disease. Abdominal ultrasound on 6/23/20 shows borderline gallbladder thickening, secondary to cirrhosis per Hepatology. Encouraged ongoing alcohol abstinence, avoid NSAIDs, and continue follow-up with hepatology. Follow with serial CBC with differential in 3 months.    # Gastric antral vascular ectasia syndrome. Upper GI endoscopy performed during hospitalization on 4/1/21 showed minimal vascular ectasia without bleeding. Continue ongoing management with GI.   #Constipation. Stable, continue lactulose as prescribed. Encouraged adequate hydration and physical activity as tolerated.   Most recent platelet count on 4/19/21 was back up to 78. Overall, there was minimal concern that patient's thrombocytopenia was due to potential immunologic mechanism related to mRNA vaccine (Moderna), but rather it was felt that this was likely a coincidental GI bleed (patient was on Aspirin at time of GI bleed as well) with consumptive thrombocytopenia on top of chronic thrombocytopenia. There was also minimal response to IVIG and Dexamethasone treatment. However, given the recent concerns with the DNA vaccines and potential thrombotic thrombocytopenia case reports, it was felt that this should be reported to VAERS. Thank you.
OTHER_MEDS: 1) Omeprazole 40 mg daily 2) Sucralfate 1 g BID 3) Spironolactone 50 mg once daily 4) Lactulose 20 grams TID 5) Insulin aspart - 16 units TID with meals plus sliding scale 6) Insulin detemir - 32 units QHS 7) Carvedilol 3.125 mg BID 8) DuoN

The lady that gave me the immunization rubbed my arm with disinfectant then looked away at something or someone, then went on to give me the shot about two inches above from were she had rubbed my arm with the disinfectant. In that moment I was just concerned with not having that area disinfected, but since I felt no pain I was happy and I thought she was the greatest. In that same evening I began experiencing pain in my arm. My arm has been in so much pain and my range of motion with that arm is about two inches. When I first stared to feel that my arm was hurting I attributed that to the vaccine. I then stared noticing that I was loosing the range of motion with that arm and yet I had no other symptoms from the vaccine.  Every night the pain is intolerable as my arm hurts so much, even when doing nothing. Even the pull from gravity makes my arm hurt. I went to the Health Department on April 19, 2021 to let them know what was going on with my arm and that I have no other symptoms and they totally dismissed my concern, they said, that since it is not bruised or swollen there is no reason to be concerned. They did say that the shot was given to me in a unusual high spot, but that it  was nothing to be concerned about. They also said that it was totally normal to have arm pain after the vaccine and didn?t even acknowledge that I can?t move my arm and that I am in so much pain. I ended up going to urgent care and the doctor there gave me a splint and said that this was normal pain due to the vaccine. He put me off of work for two days, but my arm is not getting any better. On 4/21 I went to follow up with my primary physician as the pain on my should was expanding and now I have shooting pains toward my neck. She gave me tramadol and ibuprofen for the pain, she also told me to ice my arm and do range of motion stretches. I went back to the doctor on 4/26 as the pain has not gotten better. I have some improvement in my range of motion as I have been doing the stretches that the doctor advised me to do but the pain in my shoulder is still very intense, especially at night. I was told to continue taking tramadol and to now apply heat to my shoulder. She told me to give the healing process more time as my bursa keeps healing.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Pt was seen in the Covid vaccine clinic for his second dose of moderna vaccine. Pt stated to this nurse that he typically passes out after receiving a vaccine or blood draw. This RN advised pt to sit in the same chair for his 15 min observation period. At approximately 1642 Pt started slumping over in his chair and was unresponsive to voice. His eyes were open, his skin become very pale and was diaphoretic. This Rn along with several RNs that were near by came to his aid. VS were obtained. At 1644 pt lost consciousness for approximately 15 to 30 seconds, EMS was called at this time (1644). Right before pt woke up he had witnessed convulsions. Upon waking, pt was lip smacking, no emesis at this time. His eyes were open and he was supporting his own weight but was not responding to voice commands. At approximately 1646 pt was alert and responding appropriately, stated that he knew where he was now and he was no longer confused. Pt was given an apple juice which he was able to drink without complications. At 1708 pt was A&O x4, had a steady gait, stated that he felt back to baseline and safe to drive home. Pt declined EMS evaluation and left the clinic.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: The day I received the Janssen vaccine, I had pain at the injection site immediately, which was to be expected. My arm was very sore for over a week. I felt ill at dinnertime but was able to eat. Around 10:30 PM I started to feel like my skin was on fire. It was hot to the touch as well. However, I was freezing and couldn't get warm. My teeth were chattering. I started crying uncontrollably. I have never had tears run so hard down my face. The tears felt like they were burning my skin because my skin felt so hot. I awoke my husband to help me. He wanted to take me to the Emergency Room, but I wanted to wait. My muscles ached terribly. I had to pace back and forth because of the intense pain. My head also felt like it was going to blow off of my body. It wasn't like a normal headache. It felt like I had swelling in my brain. The left side of my head was sore for days afterwards. I then became terribly nauseated. I didn't throw up but felt like I was going to. I also felt extremely dehydrated. I was able to drink some water. It was a very long night. Looking back, I probably should have gone to the ER. My husband worked from home the next day so he could be available if needed. It took a long time for me to fully recover. I woke up exhausted and struggled with fatigue for a while and had extreme exhaustion in the evenings. My ears would turn bright red in the evenings and feel hot to the touch. I still have some fatigue now but am mostly better.
OTHER_MEDS: Insulin; Emergency C packets; vitamin D drops
PRIOR_VAX: Flu vaccine 20 plus years ago. Got very sick with flu symptoms. Nothing like the symptoms with the Janssen vaccine.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient, a 51 yo Female born 04/27/1969, sitting in the observation area complaining of dizziness status post first vaccine of Pfizer.  Client stated symptoms began 5 minutes post vaccination, she denied headache, nausea, vomiting, diarrhea and any other symptoms. Client was alert and oriented to time, situation, place and person (CAOx4). Client was able to stand and walk on her own to the zero gravity chair for evaluation with a steady gait. At 0915 baseline vitals while sitting : Blood pressure (BP) 118/78, Respiratory Rate (RR) 12, heartrate (HR) 78, pupils were equal, accommodating, round and reactive to light (PEARRL), skins were normal color for ethnicity, warm and dry. EMT reassessed compliant of dizziness and client stated the symptom had subsided. Client stated she had not had anything to eat and had minimal fluid intake. Client denied history of dizziness following injections or vaccines and reported she takes aspirin daily. At 0925 second set of vitals while standing taken: BP 118/78, RR 12, HR 62, PEARRL, CAOx4, skin warm and dry. Client negative for orthostatic pressures. Client stated dizziness was fully resolved, she accepted a bottle of water and was advised to stay an additional 15 minutes for a total of 30 minutes observation. At 0942 client stated she had fully recovered from complaint of dizziness. She left observation site by self ambulation and had a steady gait.

As a citizen I took the Moderna vaccine on 15 APR 20201. Four days after taking the vaccine I developed a blood clot in my heart.  On the morning of 19 APR 2021 at 0730 I began having chest pain, I thought I had pulled a muscle while exercising the night before. Throughout the morning the pain in my chest got worse until  I called  emergency services. The EMTs told me I had a blood clot in my heart and rushed me to the hospital. Once at the hospital I  had an angioplasty . No stint was inserted.   After the surgery the doctors told me I had very large veins and a strong heart after the clot was removed  flow returned and no stint was needed.   The doctors also told me that they could not rule out the COVID vaccine as the cause of my blood clot as the rest of me heart looked good with no visible plaques or build up.   Official Diagnosis Anterior STEMI- POBA ot LAD Integrillin infusion Fit and Well Moderna vaccine 1 week ago  Diagnostic Findings -Left Main Stem - Normal LMS Left Anterior Descending- LAD 100 % stenosis restored flow   Conclusion -Aspirin 75 mg od for life - prasugrel 10mg of for 1 year - ECHo Sec prevention, Integrillin infusion 24 hrs - Card rehab  I work out every day- prior to the blood clot  Blood clot left in heart chamber- taking blood thinners to dissolve.

I was admitted at 5:16 PM CDT on 13 March 2021 to  Medical Center, to treat multiple, bi-lateral pulmonary embolism. While still in the emergency room, I was injected with a blood thinner. I was released from the hospital on 15 March 2021, with a prescription for APIXABAN (Eliquis), which I am required to take for 6-months. I was directed to see my primary care physician within 3-weeks of being discharged.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient is a 30 year old male who has completed a 30-minute observation period with the following signs and symptoms of an adverse reaction: loss of consiousness and other - syncopal episode, dizziness. Pt endorsed that he is nervous after getting the vaccine, then felt dizzy. while sitting down, he tried to distract himself by checking his cellphone then felt anxious and passed out. History of anxiety with procedures and riding the plane per patient. . Hx of having dizziness and felt like fainting on his 1sr COVID 19 vaccine. Per pt, he ate breakfast with oatmeal. Pt also endorsed he is athletic. Pt endorse that he drank 2 beers last night. Denies taking any blood thinners or Aspirin.    Staff found patient on the ground with some jerking of arms, LOC lasted for 15-30 seconds per RN. Pt placed on wheelchair and sent to evaluation area set up with gurney.   Physical exam shows abrasion on the right tempo/parietal area otherwise no step offs and no laceration. No spinall midline tenderness. Not intoxicated. No focal neuro deficit. Not taking any anticoagulants. Otherwise physical exam unremarkable, improved, and stable.   Gave Concussion educational teaching and monitoring for 24 hours and ED precautions. This is not an allergic reaction. This is more likely vasovagal syncope with fall, head injury and abrasion on right tempo/parietal area. To send home with transport. Stable to go home.    Called attending Dr., discussed case and plan for patient. Agreed with the plan.

15 mins post-vaccination: patient developed superficial numbness on skin R side of face, eyes, nose, mouth & chin. Sensation spread to R side forehead, mouth, tongue & back of throat. Stayed on R side. No dysphagia, no SOB, no HA or visual changes, no chest pain, no notable muscle weakness, no facial paralysis, no rash, no tongue swelling, VS stable, talking clearly, sipping water & complaining of numbness on tongue. Patient suddenly grabbed lower neck & throat c/o pain & feeling of tightness & pressure. Felt nauseous, like vomiting. Became apprehensive and at first was alert & oriented but then had difficulty answering questions & speaking.  BP declined to 100/50, O2 decreased to 90%, lungs had decreased breath sounds with no wheezes.  Epipen administered at 1000. VS stabilized: BP 130/60, P 100, R18, O2 sat returned to 98%. Pt was apprehensive, drowsy, confused and had difficulty answering questions.  Transport to ER via EMS. Mental status deteriorated en route, 50mg diphenhydramine administered. Abnormal clenching/tension of hands & lower extremities. Arrived at ER 1040; did not respond to triage nurse. Pulse 114.  EKG scan performed on arrival. CMP, CBC, HCG drawn. Dexamethasone 10mg & lorazepam 1mg administered. EKG, tox screen & MRI performed; all unremarkable. Patient became able to ambulate and use bathroom with minimal assistance. Became awake and oriented and could answer questions, but felt groggy. Discharged at 1446. ER visit 3 hours.
LAB_DATA: Labwork, EKG & MRI as described above
OTHER_MEDS: Trokendi 200mg daily (took dose night before) Venlafaxine 75mg qd? Pravastatin? 20mg qd? Trazodone 25-50mg hs ? Rizatriptan 5mg prn migraine?
ALLERGIES: Naprosyn- throat/face/tongue swelling & angioedema Versed- reaction unknown

On April 10, 2021 I received my 2nd dose of moderna vaccine. The following day, my arm felt sore and I felt feverish. I went to bed that night (took a nyquil)  still feeling feverish and my arm still sore. By the next morning I was feeling better and the soreness in my arm was gone but instead I felt  pain that starts from my upper arm and goes all the way down to my forearm. Sometimes, I feel a tightness that starts around my neck area and goes down to my upper arm and will always linger on my forearm. I get this sharp, intense pain throughout the day. I tried icing it, I tried tylenol, aleve, ibuprofen, Icy Hot, ben gay, and salonpas. None seems to work. After about a week, I went to see my doctor and she prescribed Gabapentin for the pain. My doctor didn't really know what was causing the pain in my arm since the vaccine is still new. Unfortunately, I had to stop taking the medicine in about a week since it didn't help with the pain and it caused me to have blurry vision and insomnia. It is now April 26 and I'm still experiencing the same pain in my left arm. I have not been able to sleep on my left side and have a hard time sleeping at night due to the pain. Tomorrow I will email my doctor.

(all dates are 2021)He had his first COVID vaccine on Feb 2nd - then he went to Punta Cana on Feb 3rd. He got a lot of sun while there, and when he returned had extensive light spots on his skin. He has a photo on his phone dated Feb 6th that showing no hypopigmentation the central chest or abdomen and only faint hypopigmentation at the flanks. He was evaluated in clinic on Feb 18th and noted to have hypopigmented annular patches extensive on the trunk and upper thighs.  He was treated with ketoconazole shampoo and cream and ciclopirox cream. His 2nd COVID vaccine was March 2nd.   From his Feb 18th visit to the April 15th visit, the hypopigmented areas on the trunk became depigmented and hypopigmentation spread to arms and legs.  His skin lesions did not respond to treatment prescribed on Feb 19th.  Biopsy done on April 15, 2021 was consistent with inflammatory vitiligo.  Unknown if coincidental that vitiligo developed at that time, but temporal correlation and fast progression is suspicious for vaccine relation.
LAB_DATA: Pathology report by CTA Pathology:   4/15/2021: Skin biopsy via 4 mm punch on R rib cage: VITILIGO COMMENT: The office note and clinical image are reviewed. Taken together, the findings are compatible with inflammatory vitiligo. There is some preservation of melanin pigment within the follicular epithelium, however, melanocytes are largely absent. No significant lymphoid atypia is observed.  In the appropriate clinical context, the histologic differential diagnosis includes chemical leukoderma.  MICROSCOPIC: Sections show an almost complete loss of epidermal melanocytes and epidermal melanin, as highlighted  by a Sox-10 immunostain and a Fontana Masson stain. No fungal forms are identified on a PAS-D stain (Immunohistochemical studies were performed with appropriate controls. The USFDA has not approved this test, but FDA approval is not required for clinical use.) All controls show appropriate reactivity.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 5 days after the first injection in my left upper arm, I developed a silver dollar sized rash on my back near my left shoulder blade.  Within 2 more days I developed more rash areas, all in the upper left quadrant of my body,  above my left breast, under my left arm, and around the original rash site near shoulder blade.  The rash felt itchy, but touching it did not relieve an itch, it was just painful.   This was accompanied by fatigue and headaches, which had continued since the day of injection.  Pain escalated, and I applied cortisone cream and took ibuprofen;  pain made it difficult to sleep;  waking up several times in night in pain.  I did not receive communication until 2 weeks after first vaccination;  I reported this adverse condition but did not receive any phone call or further communication until second 'weekly after vaccination check-in'.    I did not realize this was shingles until a friend mentioned similar experience, and I scheduled a visit to my family doctor, who diagnosed Shingles.  I received the anti-viral and am better.  I am frustrated with lack of follow up by CDC from the first vaccination (2 weeks later) and then no follow up when I reported rash.  I feel like a guinea pig, I feel like a test number, and would have appreciated some reassurance from someone at the CDC while going through this.  I don't feel like the vaccine alone caused the shingles, but I am in the process of moving, and would have delayed getting the vaccine until after the stress of the move was over, or would have gotten the Shingles vaccine, but was never directed to do so by my family doctor or anyone at the vaccine location.  Very dissatisfied.
LAB_DATA: Doctor diagnosed shingles after visually examining me on April 18 - prescribed Vanacyclavyr antiviral.  It greatly helped reduce symptoms and discomfort within 1 day.  Still have rash, today is April 26, with lessening symptoms everyday.

Patient presents with a potential reaction to the COVID19 vaccine. I was called to the patient's car outside of the vaccination area at the traffic circle for a report of a patient not breathing. Upon arrival, the patient was responsive, but minimally. She was pale and diaphoretic. The patient was placed in the supine position with legs up. Her airway was open. There was no sign of systemic allergic reaction of anaphylaxis. Rather, presentation was consistent with a severe vasovagal episode with syncope. EMS was summoned. The patient's pulse, BP and SpO2 were WNL on initial exam. The patient was moved back to the monitoring area. Over time, the patient became more responsive, however, began to have significant emesis on multiple occasions. She was not able to tolerate oral hydration. SL Zofran 4mg was given via EMS. Emesis abated. The patient was moved to the stretcher in the ambulance. A peripheral IV was started and 1000ml NS was given. BG was 121. Patient's level of consciousness improved, however, emesis remained profuse and dark in color.  Plan: Patient presented with a severe vasovagal episode with subsequent severe emesis with an inability to tolerate PO fluids. Despite SL Zofran and 1000ml of NS, symptoms didn't improve. As such, patient was transferred via EMS to the ED.
LAB_DATA: 4/25/2021  CBC with Diff, Comp metabolic panel, ECG 12 Lead, Tropinin I- Glucose High at IFG

Pt. received first Pfizer covid vaccine at 5:45pm. He was brought to the observation area for 30 minutes of observation due to hx of anaphylaxis to penicillin. At approximately 5:55pm, RNs noticed that Pt had his head in his hands. When questioned, he stated he didn?t feel well. He was helped to the ground and his legs were elevated. His vitals were 190/90, P 88, Resp 34. The nurses helped him to a sitting position as he was feeling better and he answered some medical history questions. He shared that he was Type I Diabetic. He stated he checked his blood sugar last yesterday. He ate breakfast today and took insulin. No food since this morning. Patient had no symptoms of anaphylaxis and no chest pain or other complaints. Patient denied SOB or ?throat tightening?. No hives. Patient became diaphoretic and stated he was overheated. RNs helped to remove his shirt. Observation RN alerted Nurse practitioner of the ongoing incident. Nurse Practitioner went to seek sugar sources, suspecting the patient was severely hypoglycemic. Patient, still conscious and responsive and sitting up, took 10 oz. orange juice and frosting was massaged by APRN, in buccal area with patient consent. Patient initially seemed to be improving per APRN and RNs caring for patient. BP was 170/90 at next check. P 80.  Regular respirations. Still no anaphylaxis symptoms (no hives, no angioedema, no throat tightening or wheezing). A few minutes later, Pt started shaking and said he was chilled. Patient was returned to supine position with legs elevated. He continued to shake and patient lips blue ? sweatshirt placed over him. RN noted that Pts? eyes rolled back in his head. RN went to alert the Clinical Team Manager/RN of the situation and stated that 911 should be called as patient not improving. Clinic Team Manager/RN concurred. While RNs stayed with patient and informed patient?s friend about what would occur, Clinic Site Manager  called 911. BP 140/80 at next check. Patient continued to sweat and have chills. Rescue squad arrived ? blood sugar was 116. After emergency services assessment of patient, emergency services checked blood sugar again and it had dropped to 88 within those ~5 minutes. Patient was taken by Emergency Services at 6:36pm. RN  noted that the patient remained with emergency services in parking lot  for several minutes and then pt was transported to the hospital by the emergency services. His wallet, glasses and hat were given to his friend who had accompanied patient to the vaccination clinic. His friend stated that she would call patient?s wife to inform her that patient was taken to ED by emergency services.
LAB_DATA: blood sugar tested by EMS using glucometer: 116 upon arrival; dropped to 88 a few minutes later. no other tests/lab results available.
OTHER_MEDS: insulin taken in AM without checking blood sugar

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Within 3-5 minutes of receiving the vaccine, patient starting complaining of difficulty breathing that quickly progressed to the inability to speak. Patient noted to have some airway inflammation and very large adenoids. Within another minute she started to lose consciousness. Epinephrine 0.3 mg IM was administered via EpiPen alonge with Diphenhydramine 50 mg IM. Patient responded within 1 minute and improved to the point of speaking freely, drinking water, and reporting full recovery. Patient was moved to the Emergency Department for additional monitoring and treatment where she received methylprednisolone and famotidine. Patient was discharged home later that day. Patient reports full recovery and willingness to receive the booster dose. A second dose, using Janssen vaccine is planned. Patient also now reports that she had a previous similar reaction to receiving a Vitamin B12 injection.

Per the vaccine recipient: I got the second Moderna vaccine on March 23rd at approximately 9 am. At 10:00 that night, my right foot started swelling and hurting.  I went to the doctor on March 25th and the doctor thought I may have gout. The doctor sent me home on Naproxen. On March 29th, the doctor called to tell me that my bloodwork was negative for gout. I told the doctor that the pain was in both legs now and that both feet were swelling. My doctor ordered prednisone for 2 weeks, which I took. My doctor referred me to a feet and ankle specialist, and on 4/19, I told the specialist when I received the vaccine and when the problems occurred. She did state that it could of came from the vaccine. On 4/23, I had an ultrasound on both legs to check for DVT, and it was negative. The feet and ankle specialist now is referring me to a neurologist. My first appt to go there is Monday May 3, 2021. My doctor ordered gabapentin after I finished the 2-week course of prednisone. My feet and legs still hurt, I have a sharp pain go up from my legs to the front and back of my thigh.   My feet continue to swell and I can not wear closed toe shoes.  If I attempt to walk fast, sharp pain occurs in my legs and my thighs.

Day 3)  Arm nearly normal Muscle aches gone Diarrhea began by 10 am Nausea returned - moderate, gagging no vomiting Headache worsened with extreme vertigo by noon Face tightens again - like wearing a tight scuba mask. Day 4  Fine upon waking - no pains Headache and Vertigo return by 10 am, both debilitating Moderate Nausea returns Diarrhea returns Fever less - 100.0 Overall feels like a very bad migraine with nausea and GI trouble, slight fever, and face muscles still intermittently 'tight'.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Approx. March 19, I started having headaches under right eyebrow and begin to take some Advil. During a 6 month well child check up, the child was supposed to receive a Pentacel vaccine (Dtap, Hib, Polio), but instead they were given a Kinrix vaccine (Dtap, Polio) - that vaccine is labeled for use in 4-6 year olds.  This was not noted at the time, but noted in a chart review on 4/26/2021.   The nurse that day was not familiar with the vaccines and did not seek guidance/help.  She asked anothe staff member to administer the vaccines for her because she was not comfortable giving them to a 6 month old.  That staff member just gave the vaccines that nurse prepared and did not verify what she was giving and the age of the child before administration.  Made the NCIR aware, facility incident report done, made mother aware, and staff will be educated.  No harm came to the child.

Approximately 19 hours post-vaccine, I began off-cycle, irregular bleeding from my vagina. The bleeding was light (did not fill a tampon) and lasted approximately 24 hours. I experienced NO other symptoms that I typically experience with withdrawal bleeding (e.g., cramping, lower back pain, headache). It went away in the afternoon, around 2:00pm. It returned at night, briefly before bed time at around 11:00pm. Day 4 the cough was all day. On and off. If I got excited and if I moved around too much it felt like an asthma cough. I would then feel uncomfortable in my breathing. It persisted all day. At night I could not lay down to sleep. I needed to be propped up. I needed to use my Alvesco inhaler. Day 5, In the morning the cough was not immediate, I used an air purifier the entire night and day. Used the Inhaler again. My breathing felt unconformable but it was not as bad as day 4. Day 6, the cough was gone. Only when going up stairs or moving around too much did it come back for a few mins then would go away. Inhaler used again at night. No air purifier. Am able to sleep laying down again. Day 7 I am feeling better now and no longer have discomfort breathing. No longer need inhaler.
OTHER_MEDS: Acetaminophen Extra Strength, Alvesco Ciclesonide Inhaler 80mcg/ acutation

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 2 weeks after his first COVID vaccine on 3/20/2021, patient developed a rash, located on the dorsal/lateral feet, legs and arms; red and bumpy but not itchy.  He was seen on 4/9/2021 at which time he had small ~2-3 mm purplish macules and slightly elevated papules on the thighs, lower legs and very faint on the right flexor forearm.    A biopsy of the skin was done on 4/9/2021 and he was treated with Triamcinolone 0.1%  cream pending biopsy results.  The patient had his second COVID vaccine on 4/10/2021 and patient reported his rash spreading on his arms on 4/12/2021.    biopsy results returned on 4/14/2021 and showed urticarial hypersensitivity reaction.  He was continued on Triamcinolone 0.1%  cream and Zyrtec 10 mg po qhs and Claritin 10 mg po qam were started.    He was seen on 4/21/2021 and exam showed: Arms and legs have small erythematous papules, monomorphic and less than 3 mm each, on the distal arms and legs. The most numerous are on the dorsal wrist and lateral feet bilaterally. His palms and soles are clear. The more proximal lesions present on the lower legs and forearms are not as erythematous and appear to be fading; previously affected area on the R flexor forearm at last visit is clear today. The ones on the thighs also appear to be fading with mostly post inflammatory hyperpigmentation remaining. The mid to low back, flanks and abdomen are clear except for two similar erythematous papules on the left flank  He was continued on Triamcinolone 0.1%  cream and Claritin 10 mg po qam; zyrtec was discontinued due to sleepiness.  On 4/22/2021 and 4/23/2021 patient sent patient portal messages showing new linear purplish plaques developing.  Labs were sent which were unremarkable.  Felt to be dermatographism and zyrtec restarted at lower dose of 5 mg po qhs.
LAB_DATA: 4/9/2021 Skin 3.5 mm punch biopsies: A. SKIN, LEFT THIGH, BIOPSY: URTICARIAL HYPERSENSITIVITY REACTION. COMMENT: The findings are compatible with an urticarial hypersensitivity reaction. Although not entirely specific, these reactions have been described secondary to COVID-19 vaccines. There is no evidence of vasculitis. Dr., a Board-certified dermatopathologist, has reviewed this case and concurs. B. SKIN, LEFT THIGH, BIOPSY: NEGATIVE DIRECT IMMUNOFLUORESCENCE STUDY.  4/23/2021 CBC with diff within normal limits (platelet count 169 normal) Cr/BUN/SGOT/SGPT are within normal limits

I periodically experience aphthous ulcers in my mouth that respond very consistently (100%) to treatment with topical Triamcinolone Acetonide. Even a single application will significantly reduce the size, duration, and severity of a developing ulcer.  I happened to have two small aphthous ulcers at the time I got the second dose of the Moderna vaccine, and those ulcers were completely nonresponsive to what became very aggressive treatment (topical Triamcinolone Acetonide 4x daily for 2 weeks.)  The size, duration, and severity (pain) of those two ulcers were as if they were completely untreated, despite continuous, aggressive treatment. (Ulcers grew to several millimeters in diameter, took ~2 weeks to subside, caused severe pain that interfered with eating/brushing/talking.)  I did not happen to have any aphthous ulcers at the time of the first dose of the vaccine. I also experienced whole body aches, chills, and fatigue with both doses of the vaccine.
PRIOR_VAX: Whole body aches, chills, fatigue with Moderna COVID-19 dose 1.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient was asked how she was feeling about 10 minutes after the vaccine and she said she was feeling fine. When patient left 30 minutes after receiving vaccine, she said she thought that she could feel the vaccine going up her arm and shoulder, but she said she was ok. About 30 minutes later, the patient came back to the vaccine area and said that she felt swelling on the left side of her neck and was having a lot of phlegm in her throat. She said that she drank water. She said her breathing was fine. I immediately offered her Benadryl, but she did not want to take it because she said it makes her tired for 3 days afterward. She stood and talked for about 10 minutes and she was not feeling better, but did not appear worse. She still denied to take Benadryl, so I sent her home with 2 Benadryl 25 mg tablets and a bottle of water. I told her if she's not feeling better in 15-30 minutes, that she should take the tablets. I let her know if she gets any worse or if Benadryl does not provide relief, he should call 911 or go to the ER. I told the patient to contact her PCP to let them know about the reaction. The patient was with her husband. I called her husband at 1:32 pm,  and he said that the reaction was "easing off," and she had not taken the Benadryl. I tried calling back around 5:45 pm and there was no answer.

My mother suffered a massive stroke 40 days after receiving the 2nd dose of the cover 19 vaccine. She fell sick the day after the injection and suffered with brain fog, memory issues, lethargy from that day forward. On day 36 after the 2nd dose she developed a debilitating stomach issue that cause explosive diarrhea that lasted 4 days/nights. This bout with stomach issues left her extremely weak and exhausted. On the 4th night of the diarrhea she got up in the middle of the night to go to the bathroom and couldn't lift herself off of the commode. It took two hours for her to call for help. Once admitted to the ER the stroke was confirmed. Because they could not pinpoint the first stroke symptom she was not eligible for the life saving blood thinning meds and suffered complete paralysis of her right side.
LAB_DATA: Hospital MRI on 3/27/21 confirming an ischemic stroke in the posterior limb of internal capsule.

Took some Tylenol, which was a bit helpful.  No fevers.  Pain is primarily along the entire deltoid.  No tingling in the hand.  No rash.  Has had prior vaccination without issue.  Has not had any other vaccines in the past 10 years.  Does not think he had pertussis in the 10 years since his last vaccine, though he had a severe "flu" about 6 years ago that lasted only a few days.  left deltoid with small, yellowing bruise at location that is consistent with IM injection.  There is no visible redness, rash, or obvious swelling of the left upper arm.  AC joint is not painful to palpation.   No pain with palpation of the elbow.  Tender along the distal body of the deltoid.  Strong grasp.  Tolerates PROM of the shoulder, but pain with elevation >45 degrees and with internal/external rotation.  Can reach cross-body, but this causes pain.  Negative empty can test.  Reviewed the package insert on the Tdap.  Class 3 pain (quantified as pain the prevents typical activity) can occur in 1.6% of patients in the 15 days post-injection.  He is afebrile, appears well, no alarming findings on exam.  Suspect he is having an exaggerated vaccine response.  Can use ice/heat, OTC lidocaine patches, and NSAIDs.  Will submit VAERS report.  He should reach out if anything is worsening or not starting to improve in the next week or so.  He verbalized understanding and agreed.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient is a 69-year-old woman with newly diagnosed pericarditis in March 2021, hypertension, hyperlipidemia, and hypothyroidism, who presented to the Emergency Department (ED) with progressively worsening chest pain, dyspnea, and fatigue. Patient was in her usual state of health until 3/1/2021, when she developed sudden-onset pain "across the entire chest".  She shares that her symptoms "came out of the blue", as "suddenly one day, everything just hurt".  She saw her primary care physician, who initially felt her symptoms were due to acid reflux.  As such, the patient started "eating antacids and omeprazole like candy".  However, her chest pain persisted, prompting her to follow up with her primary care physician on 3/16/2021.  At that time, ECG reportedly showed normal sinus rhythm and no acute changes.  CT of the chest, abdomen, and pelvis with contrast showed abnormal enhancement and thickening of the pericardium with trace pericardial fluid, consistent with pericarditis.  The patient was therefore started on colchicine and an ibuprofen taper.   On 4/5/2021, Patient sent a myVM portal message to her primary care physician and cardiologist, expressing her belief that her chest pain has remained unchanged over the past month.  She continues to experience a constant burning sensation throughout her chest, aggravated by deep inspiration and alleviated by lying flat on her back.  She shares that walking up the stairs at home leaves her "breathless".  Associated symptoms include subjective fevers, chills, and night sweats.  Given these symptoms, Patient underwent a chest x-ray, which showed findings consistent with an enlarging pericardial effusion.  Patient was then advised to present to the ED for further workup as an inpatient.   At time of hospital admission, patient endorses persistent chest pain during inspiration.  Prior to 3/1/2021, she has never experienced these symptoms and reports no history of pericarditis.  The most strenuous physical activity she has undertaken in the last month include working in the garden and caring light boxes down the stairs.  She is most concerned about the fluid around her heart.  Patient reports no nausea, vomiting, palpitations, constipation, diarrhea, or abdominal pain.  Of note, the patient developed pericarditis 10 days after her second COVID-19 vaccine.  Hospital Course        # Sub-acute pericarditis with enlarging pericardial effusion Pericarditis initially diagnosed in March 2021, thought to be potentially from her COVID-19 vaccine given time course as no other clear etiology apparent.  Pt was hemodynamically stable with an elevated jugular venous pressure at time of admission, with CXR consistent with an enlarging pericardial effusion. Echo 04/05 with small circumferential pericardial effusion but no tamponade physiology.  Cardiac MRI on 4/7 with enlargement of moderate-sized pericardial effusion but otherwise negative exam, with no evidence of myocarditis or infiltrative myocardial process. ANA screen negative, rheumatoid factor and anti-CCP not elevated Blood cultures x 2 with no growth - CRP continued to remain > 160 with ibupofen and colchicine. Prednisone 20 mg PO daily was added on 4/7, with subsequent improvement in patient's symptoms.   - Discharged on regimen of prednisone 20 mg PO daily and colchicine 0.3 mg PO daily (reduced from 0.6 mg daily that she was taking prior to admission). She will also continue using ibuprofen 800 mg BID.  - Follow-up with Dr (cardiology) next week to follow-up on hospitalization and decide upon tapering plan for her medications
LAB_DATA: CXR 04/05 with enlarged cardiac silhouette that has developed since the March 1, 2021 exam. Given the visible change in one month a pericardial  effusion should be suspected.   TTE 04/05 with small circumferential pericardial effusion but no tamponade physiology, EF normal (68%), CVP mildly elevated at 8    Cardiac MRI 04/07 Impression: 1. Compared to 3/16/2021 there has been enlargement in now a  moderate-sized pericardial effusion. Findings are nonspecific and  could be related to pericarditis but there is no abnormal pericardial  thickening. 2. New small bilateral pleural effusions. 3. Otherwise negative exam. No evidence of myocarditis or  infiltrative myocardial process.
OTHER_MEDS: As of Jan 28 2021 1. Flonase 1 spray b.i.d. as needed. 2. Levothyroxine 100 mcg daily. 3. Lisinopril 20 mg a day.   4. Omeprazole 40 mg daily. 5. Sumatriptan 25 mg p.r.n. 6. Pravastatin 40 mg daily. 7. Cetirizine 10 mg daily.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: After receiving her first dose of the Moderna Covid-19 Vaccine at 10:55 a.m., the patient fainted while in her chair in the waiting area and had convulsions.  We immediately called 911 and we were able to get the patient to the floor safely and elevate her legs. Her convulsions stopped shortly after they began, and I stayed at the patient's side.  She had normal breathing and pulse and began to wake up shortly after her legs were elevated.  I applied a cold pack to the patient's forehead with her consent.  She was very disoriented upon waking up.  EMS arrived at 11:08 a.m. and took her blood pressure and blood glucose reading.  She was conscious when they arrived but still disoriented.  Her blood pressure was low and the patient said she felt like she was going to pass out again after they stuck her finger to check glucose.  EMS transported the patient to Hospital because of her persistent low blood pressure.  I attempted to call the patient this evening to check on her but was unable to reach her.
PRIOR_VAX: Dizziness after a previous vaccine

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Reaction to the first dose was mild. Within 12 hours of receiving the second dose, I experienced headache, fever (highest reading was 102.6) and violent chills that lasted for several hours. Chills stopped and fever broke at around 36 hours. Extremely fatigued and slept or rested most of 48 hours.  Also developed a lingering cough but no shortness of breath. Constant bad taste in mouth, and food tastes bitter so no appetite. Pain at injection site went away quickly, but still have pain further down left arm and in lymph nodes. Feeling better at 72 hour mark, but tired and still have bad taste in mouth so everything tastes bitter. The main reason I'm reporting this is that I would like to pose a question -- Since women tend to have more negative reactions to the vaccine than men, and women tend to have more autoimmune issues than men, could there be a connection? Could that be why I had such a bad reaction to the second dose? My autoimmune issues are mild, but I have several. I need to take a corticosteroid for Crohn's disease but have deliberately delayed beginning treatment until two weeks after my second dose (May 8, 2021). I wasn't able to find much information about this. Thank you.

LAB_DATA: 4/5/21 Blood test- Cyclic Citrullinated Peptide Igg, ANA w/Relex Antibody ID & Titer, C-Reactive Protein, CBCW/Diff(Auto) CPK(Ck). Complement-Total Hemolytic (CH50), ESR (Sed Rate), Automated, Immunoglobulins, Iga, Igg, Igm, Metabolic Comprehensive, Rheumatoid Fact (Ra), TSH, Uric Acid.  Doctor's report back on test results: I have received and reviewed your lab results. Your comprehensive laboratory evaluation for your joint pains is quite reassuring with no significant concerning findings. Your complement level (CH-50), CRP, & ESR are elevated, which are all acute-phase reactants and can be elevated due to a number of reasons. However, given recent vaccination and rather robust response to vaccination, I would be most inclined to think that this is due to vaccination with a robust immune/body response to vaccination. CH50 or individual proteins, such as C3 or C4, may increase up to 50 percent of baseline values as part of the acute-phase response, or response to infection, inflammation, or in this case, vaccination. Beyond this, an elevated CH50 has no specific clinical significance. This is an expected part of your body's immune response. High levels in themselves do not lead to tissue damage, as the proteins are not in their activated state, and regulators tend to increase in parallel. Low levels are much more concerning for a complement deficiency. Thus, I do not see any clear reason or indication for further evaluation or intervention at this time.  I would recommend following care plan discussed during your recent visit.  Thank you, DO  Probable EKG test pending 4/27/21

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Female patient reported no history of issues with vaccine. Arrived for administration of her second moderna dose, received it successfully. After about 10 minutes she asked for an additional bandaid, while I was wiping the blood off her arm and applying the new bandaid she said she wasn't feeling well, then fainted in her seat. I held her stable for about 15 seconds at which point she woke up and answered my questions which were: can you hear me? (yes) are you having any trouble breathing? (no) did you have something to eat this morning? (no). I provided the patient another chair to elevate her feet. I notified the other pharmacist on staff of the situation who stayed with the patient while I got a bag of chips and a soda for her. I asked her to stay a while longer until she's feeling well, then I went back to the pharmacy (while keeping the patient in view) to continue preparing and administering vaccines. The patient recovered well, laughing at herself and apologizing because she's never had this happen to her before. I assured her that no apology was necessary, I'm glad she's feeling better, and that she should stay as long as she needs. After about 15 more minutes the patient rose from her chair said that she felt fine and was going to leave to go get breakfast. I wished her well and allowed her to leave.

An hour after Pfizer vaccine administration, the parents of the 16 year old patient returned to the pharmacy and reported that their daughter was complaining of trouble breathing in the parking lot.  The immunizing tech asked the parents to bring the patient back to the pharmacy.    The patient returned and while crying and gasping for air, she reported that it felt as if someone was constricting her throat.  She also complained of stiff fingers and feeling numbness/tingling in her upper extremities.    Assuming anaphylactic reaction, one dose of epinephrine was administered.  The patient said she felt slightly better after the first dose but then 2 minutes later, said her breathing was getting worse, and again described feeling her throat tightening.  Five minutes later, a 2nd dose of epinephrine was administered.   The patient was taken to the hospital by paramedics.

Pt called back 2-3 hours after leaving from vaccine to report that her lips were tingling and her chin was tingling, and she had some flushing. She stated that she had been monitoring her vitals and that she had no trouble breathing or swelling. Pt stated that she took a Benadryl to treat it.  I told pt that if she was having any difficulty breathing she should call 911 or go to the hospital immediately. She stated that she thought she was past the anaphylactic reaction point, and she did not want to go to the doctor. I informed her that if she begins to have any trouble breathing to call 911 as soon as possible.

The adverse reactions of light headedness, throat irritation, heaviness in my chest and difficulty inhaling began about 20 min after my injection, It lasted 5 minutes. About 30 min afterwards the 2nd wave of reaction came on, with the same symptoms but was even harder to inhale and lasted twice as long. I took a combination of benadryl, motrin and pepcid which alleviated the worst of the symptoms after about an hour. To this day, I still cannot take a deep breath in.  About 72 hours after the vaccine I began to have diarrhea (and still have it 20 days later), lethargy, nausea and shortness of breath. The next day I had a little more energy, but still had continued shortness of breath. My vision had become less clear and my thought process a bit fuzzy. This is still happening today. Seven days after the vaccine,  I suddenly became extremely light headed just simply walking. To the extent that I needed to sit or lay down before I began to pass out. After the light headedness came on heavily, I also noticed a very heavy weight on my upper chest and found it quite difficult to inhale. These moments would come and go throughout the day. Regardless of whether I was just sitting and relaxing or walking around. These symptoms would last anywhere from a couple minutes to a couple of hours. I found it very hard to catch my breath and could feel my heart flushing often. Additionally I would wake in the middle of the night feeling that I needed to gasp for air. I sought medical assistance from a clinic, an ER and even my allergist and I am scheduled to see my family physician later this week.   I am not an anxious person, but have experienced many episodes in the last 20 days that have truly made me feel that I was going to die (no exaggeration!) due to the inability to breathe or that I may have been having a heart attack. I began to have chest pain that would travel from the center of my chest to my left shoulder. The pain also would move to my right lung area. During this I also had heaviness in my chest and felt I could not breathe in or out easily. I am still very light headed and have difficulty walking very far without taking a break because I feel I cannot catch my breath. I still have all of the same symptoms that I experienced 20 minutes after my vaccine. These symptoms have varied in intensity. I have often commented to my family that I feel the symptoms of the chest heaviness and heart flushing seem to come in waves. I am a health conscious person and have never had poor health in my life. The events in the last few weeks have definitely taught me how terrible life must be for those who chronically suffer from heart or lung issues. I am still currently battling these symptoms, however, the last few days seem the symptoms have often been less severe.
LAB_DATA: 2 negative COVID tests, 12 lead EKG (twice), lung CT with and w/out contrast, chest x-ray, lung function testing, a large array of lab work~ to date all tests have come back negative. If you would like to view my testing and results, you can contact me.
ALLERGIES: allergies to pollen, mold, dander, trees, flowers, cilantro

Patient came in for his 2nd Moderna shot today 4/26/21. I administered the vaccine and asked him to remain in the store for a 15-minute observation period (just like the 1st dose). After 2-3 minutes he walked to the pharmacy window to let my technician know he was starting to feel dizzy. At the same time my technician was informing me about his complaint, he lost consciousness and fell, hitting the side of his head on the consultation wall. I immediately asked technician to call 911 and rushed to get EpiPen to patient. He immediately regained consciousness. I did not administer any EpiPen doses. I stayed with him and monitored him until paramedics arrived. When paramedics arrived, they asked me which vaccine I administered and started asking patient questions. They measured his blood pressure. Patient was responsive and he called his wife to let her know he was going to the ER. Paramedic informed us that his blood pressure was low. On his way to the hospital he looked at us and said thank you. I will call him tomorrow to check on him.

Patient presented at vaccination table after having documents and appointment reviewed by non-clinical staff, and identity was confirmed by Nurse Vaccinator using two unique identifiers (including DOB). Nurse vaccinator reviewed patient's responses to screening form completed in PrepMod and screened patient to confirm she was feeling well, had no history of anaphylaxis, does not carry an epi-pen for allergies, and had not received COVID vaccine previously. Nurse vaccinator educated patient on possible side effects of Moderna product. Patient indicated she wished to be immunized, received Moderna vaccine, and proceeded to observation area where she waited for fifteen minutes before departing from clinic without reporting any adverse event. Patient then presented with parent on April 20, 2021 for second dose.  Nurse vaccinator for second dose explained that patient was under the age of 18 (DOB 02/01/2005) and was unable to be vaccinated.  The parent asked to speak to the clinical lead in COVID-19 vaccination clinic.  The clinical lead contacted the Director of Nursing who was onsite, to speak with the patient and the parent.  The DON spoke with the parent and explained the error that occurred on March 23, 2021 and that the current RN vaccinator couldn?t vaccinate the patient without written consent from the parent.  The parent requested a consent form, the DON reviewed the consent form with both the patient and parent.  Parent signed the consent form and patient was vaccinated.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: The first shot was on 02/06/2021 , the second on 03/06/2021. After the first shot, I noticed that the HGB and Retic ct abs both decreased. Then the HGB continued to decrease to 6.9 on April 22 when a blood transfusion was ordered for the next day. A bone marrow biopsy was conducted April 14, (6 weeks after the 2nd shot) and showed CLL cells taking over the sample (see page 2 sticky note). Prior to the vaccination, the blood tests were stable. It seems the vaccination excited the CLL so now significant cancer treatment is needed.
